Ι pondered too over the matter of Caelius when I read it in your letter, which I received on the same day as Ι arrived at Cumae. It was possible too that it was a mere ruse, so I did away with all grounds of suspicion. But, while I was on my way back, Hor- tensius came, and turned out of his way to greet Terentia, and he had spoken of me with much cour· tesy. I think I shall see him soon, for he has sent a servant to announce his coming. This is better behaviour than that of my fellow augur Antony, who carries an actress in a sedan among his lictors.

As you have lost your quartan fever and have not only thrown off your new malady but also your cold, you must present yourself before me sound and fit in Greece. Meanwhile drop me a. line.
